<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="2824" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="42.[120,760,1219,1955]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">
Basonym: 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharpe et al. 1973" authorityName="Sharpe" authorityYear="1973" box="[243,714,1376,1400]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="ruminis">
<emphasis box="[243,480,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">Lactobacillus ruminis</emphasis>
Sharpe 
<emphasis box="[585,639,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">et al</emphasis>
. 1973
</taxonomicName>
, 47 (Approved Lists)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[120,760,1219,1955]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">
Strains of 
<taxonomicName box="[224,330,1453,1476]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="ruminis">
<emphasis box="[224,330,1453,1476]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">L. ruminis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are motile by peritrichous flagella, anaerobic, and grow on surface only under reduced oxygen pressure; growth in liquid media is supported with the addition of cysteine–HCl. Strains isolated from sewage are nonmotile and do not grow at 45 °C [
<bibRefCitation author="Sharpe ME &amp; Latham MJ &amp; Garvie EI &amp; Zirngibl J &amp; Kandler O." box="[401,447,1576,1600]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824" pagination="37 - 49" refId="ref69674" refString="224. Sharpe ME, Latham MJ, Garvie EI, Zirngibl J, Kandler O. Two new species of Lactobacillus isolated from the bovine rumen, Lactobacillus ruminis sp. nov. and Lactobacillus vitulinus sp. nov. J Gen Microbiol 1973; 77: 37 - 49." type="journal article" year="1973">224</bibRefCitation>
]. The genome size of the 
<typeStatus box="[714,760,1577,1601]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">type</typeStatus>
strain is 2.01 Mbp. The mol% G+C content of DNA is 43.4.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[120,760,1219,1955]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824">
Isolated from rumen of cow and from sewage; also commonly found in the gut of humans, horses and pigs and bovine uterus. Genomic analyses indicated a differentiation of specific phylogenetic lineages of the species to specific vertebrate hosts [
<bibRefCitation author="Donnell MM &amp; Harris HMB &amp; Lynch DB &amp; Ross RP &amp; O'Toole PW" box="[249,295,1777,1801]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2824" pagination="80" refId="ref69726" refString="225. O' Donnell MM, Harris HMB, Lynch DB, Ross RP, O'Toole PW. Lactobacillus ruminis strains cluster according to their mammalian gut source. BMC Microbiol 2015; 15: 80." type="journal article" year="2015">225</bibRefCitation>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
